Note: ================================================================
Note: Bifrost Data Layout Optimization
Note: ================================================================
Note: Optimizes data layout for GPU memory coalescing and cache locality.
Note: Typical speedup: 10-30% from improved memory access patterns.
Note: Techniques: AoS↔SoA, row/column major, tiling, padding, transpose.
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/graph.runa" as Graph
Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/node.runa" as Node
Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/edge.runa" as Edge
Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/analysis/memory_access.runa" as MemoryAccess
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as String
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Math

Note: ================================================================
Note: Layout Type Constants
Note: ================================================================

Constant LAYOUT_ROW_MAJOR as Integer is 0        Note: C-style: [row][col]
Constant LAYOUT_COLUMN_MAJOR as Integer is 1     Note: Fortran-style: [col][row]
Constant LAYOUT_AOS as Integer is 2              Note: Array of Structures
Constant LAYOUT_SOA as Integer is 3              Note: Structure of Arrays
Constant LAYOUT_TILED as Integer is 4            Note: Blocked for cache
Constant LAYOUT_PADDED as Integer is 5           Note: Padding added for alignment

Note: ================================================================
Note: Transformation Type Constants
Note: ================================================================

Constant TRANSFORM_NONE as Integer is 0
Constant TRANSFORM_TRANSPOSE as Integer is 1      Note: Swap dimensions
Constant TRANSFORM_AOS_TO_SOA as Integer is 2     Note: Convert AoS → SoA
Constant TRANSFORM_SOA_TO_AOS as Integer is 3     Note: Convert SoA → AoS
Constant TRANSFORM_TILE as Integer is 4           Note: Apply tiling
Constant TRANSFORM_PAD as Integer is 5            Note: Add padding

Note: ================================================================
Note: Fixed-Point Scale (PPM = Parts Per Million)
Note: ================================================================
Note: Stage1 of the bootstrap chain emits idivq for canonical Float
Note: operators on IEEE 754 bit patterns, producing garbage at runtime.
Note: All speedup factors are therefore represented as fixed-point
Note: integers in PPM, where 1_000_000 represents the floating-point
Note: value 1.0.
Note:
Note:   PPM_ONE        == 1_000_000   (== 1.0x)
Note:   1_300_000 PPM  == 1.3x speedup
Note:   2_000_000 PPM  == 2.0x speedup
Note: ================================================================

Constant PPM_ONE as Integer is 1000000
Constant PPM_ZERO as Integer is 0

Note: ================================================================
Note: Type Definitions
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
DataLayout is the canonical descriptor consumed by every transformation in this module. The six fields together fully describe how an array/matrix/tensor is laid out in memory: layout_type names the family (row-major, col-major, AoS, SoA, tiled, padded), dimensions and strides describe per-dimension shape and byte stride, tile_sizes and padding are the auxiliary parameters consumed when layout_type is TILED or PADDED, and is_coalesced is a memoized coalescing test used by detect_optimal_layout to short-circuit when the current layout is already optimal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Six-slot record at offsets 0/8/16/24/32/40. analyze_current_layout populates it via field initialization. The other layout_opt procs read fields via memory_get_int64 at the documented offsets - these offsets are part of this module's internal contract.
@End Implementation

Type called "DataLayout":
    layout_type as Integer          Note: LAYOUT_* constant
    dimensions as Integer           Note: List of dimension sizes
    strides as Integer              Note: List of strides (bytes between elements)
    tile_sizes as Integer           Note: List of tile sizes (if tiled)
    padding as Integer              Note: Padding bytes per dimension
    is_coalesced as Boolean         Note: Whether layout enables coalescing
End Type

@Reasoning:
LayoutTransformation captures one proposed layout change: which node, what kind of transform (transpose, AoS-to-SoA, tile, pad), the source and target DataLayout, and the PPM-scaled cost/benefit metrics computed by estimate_layout_benefit and estimate_transformation_cost. optimize_data_layout consumes a List of these to drive the greedy pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Six-slot record at offsets 0/8/16/24/32/40. estimated_benefit_ppm and transformation_cost_ppm are PPM-scaled Integer values stored at offsets 32 and 40; the orchestrator reads them via memory_get_int64 to compute net_benefit_ppm = (benefit_ppm * PPM_ONE) / (PPM_ONE + cost_ppm).
@End Implementation

Type called "LayoutTransformation":
    transform_type as Integer            Note: TRANSFORM_* constant
    target_node as Integer               Note: Node whose layout to transform
    source_layout as Integer             Note: Original DataLayout
    target_layout as Integer             Note: Optimized DataLayout
    estimated_benefit_ppm as Integer     Note: Expected speedup in PPM (1_000_000 == 1.0x)
    transformation_cost_ppm as Integer   Note: Layout conversion cost in PPM
End Type

@Reasoning:
TilingConfig records the parameters of a single tiling decision: which dimensions are tiled, the size per tile, and which cache level the tile is sized for (L1/L2/L3). compute_optimal_tiling returns one of these for a given DataLayout.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three-slot record at offsets 0/8/16. tile_dimensions and tile_sizes are List pointers; cache_level is the integer 1/2/3 selector matching x86_64 cache hierarchy.
@End Implementation

Type called "TilingConfig":
    tile_dimensions as Integer      Note: Which dimensions to tile
    tile_sizes as Integer           Note: Size of each tile
    cache_level as Integer          Note: L1=1, L2=2, L3=3
End Type

Note: ================================================================
Note: Layout Analysis
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Reconstructs the current DataLayout for a node by combining its BifrostType (Matrix or Tensor) with any "layout" hint stored in the node's metadata dictionary. Default assumption is row-major (C convention); the metadata key "column_major" overrides this. The result is fed into detect_optimal_layout to discover transformation opportunities.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Initialize layout as row-major with dimensions/strides = 0.
2. get_node_output_type; bail with default if 0.
3. Read type discriminant at offset 0. For Matrix (3): pull rows (offset 16) and cols (offset 24), build a 2-element dimensions list, compute row-major strides via element_size = get_primitive_size(element_type at offset 8).
4. Inspect metadata for "layout" key; if "column_major", flip layout_type and rebuild strides via element_size-then-rows layout.
5. For Tensor (5): the shape list pointer is at offset 16, then compute row-major strides over that shape.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(d) where d is dimension count. The hot allocations are the dimensions and strides Lists; both are sized exactly to d. Called once per array node during the layout pass.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read of node fields and metadata. Allocates fresh layout/dimension/stride lists. Trusts the BifrostType layout offsets that are part of node.runa's contract.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "analyze_current_layout" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let layout be a value of type DataLayout with
        layout_type as LAYOUT_ROW_MAJOR,
        dimensions as 0,
        strides as 0,
        tile_sizes as 0,
        padding as 0,
        is_coalesced as false

    Note: Get output type
    Let output_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with node
    If output_type is equal to 0:
        Return layout
    End If

    Let discriminant be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 0

    Note: Matrix type
    If discriminant is equal to 3:
        Let rows be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 16
        Let cols be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 24

        Note: Create dimensions list
        Let dimensions be proc create from List
        proc append from List with dimensions, rows
        proc append from List with dimensions, cols
        Set layout.dimensions to dimensions

        Note: Compute row-major strides
        Let element_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 8
        Let element_size be get_primitive_size(element_type)

        Let strides be proc create from List
        proc append from List with strides, cols multiplied by element_size Note: Row stride
        proc append from List with strides, element_size Note: Column stride
        Set layout.strides to strides

        Note: Detect actual layout from metadata
        Let metadata be proc get_node_metadata from Node with node
        If metadata is not equal to 0:
            Let layout_hint be proc get from Dict with metadata, "layout"
            If layout_hint is equal to "column_major":
                Set layout.layout_type to LAYOUT_COLUMN_MAJOR

                Note: Update strides for column-major
                Let col_major_strides be proc create from List
                proc append from List with col_major_strides, element_size Note: Row stride
                proc append from List with col_major_strides, rows multiplied by element_size Note: Column stride
                Set layout.strides to col_major_strides
            End If
        End If

        Return layout
    End If

    Note: Tensor type
    If discriminant is equal to 5:
        Let shape_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 16
        If shape_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Set layout.dimensions to shape_ptr

            Note: Compute strides for row-major tensor
            Set element_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 8
            Set element_size to get_primitive_size(element_type)

            Set strides to compute_row_major_strides(shape_ptr, element_size)
            Set layout.strides to strides
        End If

        Return layout
    End If

    Return layout
End Process

@Reasoning:
Selects the optimal DataLayout for a node by reconciling the actual access pattern (from MemoryAccess.analyze_access_pattern) with the current layout. The objective is to make the innermost dimension contiguous in memory along the dimension that consumers iterate fastest - this is what enables GPU coalescing and CPU prefetching. Falls back to tiling for cache-bound workloads and padding for bank-conflict avoidance.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Run analyze_access_pattern; read pattern_type (offset 0) and stride (offset 8).
2. clone_layout current_layout as the starting point.
3. ACCESS_CONTIGUOUS (1): mark is_coalesced and return.
4. ACCESS_STRIDED (2): flip row-major <-> column-major and rebuild strides via compute_row_major_strides / compute_column_major_strides; mark coalesced.
5. Other patterns: consult should_apply_tiling -> compute_optimal_tiling and should_apply_padding -> compute_optimal_padding to stack tiling/padding modifiers on top of the base layout.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Single analyze_access_pattern call (O(depth of address DAG)) plus constant-time decision logic. Cost is dominated by the embedded MemoryAccess analyzer, not this proc itself.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only on graph, node, current_layout. Allocates a fresh DataLayout via clone_layout and potentially fresh stride lists.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "detect_optimal_layout" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer, current_layout as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze access pattern
    Let access_pattern be proc analyze_access_pattern from MemoryAccess with graph, node
    Let pattern_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with access_pattern, 0
    Let stride be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with access_pattern, 8

    Note: Clone current layout
    Let optimal_layout be clone_layout(current_layout)

    Note: If access is already contiguous, keep current layout
    If pattern_type is equal to 1:
        Note: ACCESS_CONTIGUOUS
        Set optimal_layout.is_coalesced to true
        Return optimal_layout
    End If

    Note: If strided access, consider transpose
    If pattern_type is equal to 2:
        Note: ACCESS_STRIDED
        Note: Get current layout type
        Let current_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_layout, 0

        Note: Transpose layout to make access contiguous
        If current_type is equal to LAYOUT_ROW_MAJOR:
            Set optimal_layout.layout_type to LAYOUT_COLUMN_MAJOR
            Note: Update strides
            Let dimensions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_layout, 8
            Let element_size be stride
            Let new_strides be compute_column_major_strides(dimensions, element_size)
            Set optimal_layout.strides to new_strides
            Set optimal_layout.is_coalesced to true
        End If

        If current_type is equal to LAYOUT_COLUMN_MAJOR:
            Set optimal_layout.layout_type to LAYOUT_ROW_MAJOR
            Set dimensions to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_layout, 8
            Set element_size to stride
            Set new_strides to compute_row_major_strides(dimensions, element_size)
            Set optimal_layout.strides to new_strides
            Set optimal_layout.is_coalesced to true
        End If

        Return optimal_layout
    End If

    Note: For other patterns, analyze tiling opportunities
    Let should_tile be should_apply_tiling(graph, node, current_layout)
    If should_tile is equal to true:
        Let tiling_config be compute_optimal_tiling(graph, node, current_layout)
        Set optimal_layout.layout_type to LAYOUT_TILED
        Set optimal_layout.tile_sizes to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with tiling_config, 8
    End If

    Note: Check if padding would help
    Let should_pad be should_apply_padding(graph, node, optimal_layout)
    If should_pad is equal to true:
        Let padding_amount be compute_optimal_padding(optimal_layout)
        Set optimal_layout.padding to padding_amount
        Set optimal_layout.layout_type to LAYOUT_PADDED
    End If

    Return optimal_layout
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Layout Transformations
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Sweeps every node in the graph, filtering down to those carrying array/matrix data (Matrix or Tensor type per node_has_layout). For each one, computes current and optimal layouts and emits a LayoutTransformation when they differ. The result is the worklist that optimize_data_layout sorts and applies greedily.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Get all nodes from the graph.
2. For each node, filter via node_has_layout.
3. analyze_current_layout -> detect_optimal_layout.
4. layouts_differ check; if true, compute transform_type via determine_transform_type, benefit via estimate_layout_benefit, cost via estimate_transformation_cost.
5. Allocate a LayoutTransformation record and append.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N * d) where N is node count and d is average dimension count - each kept node runs a constant chain of helpers, each linear in dimension count. The MemoryAccess.analyze_access_pattern subcall is the dominant cost per node.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure analysis; allocates a fresh transformations List of LayoutTransformation records. No graph mutation. Safe to run concurrently with other read-only passes.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_layout_transformations" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    Let transformations be proc create from List

    Note: Get all nodes
    Let all_nodes be proc get_all_nodes from Graph with graph
    Let node_count be proc length from List with all_nodes

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with all_nodes, i

        Note: Check if node has array/matrix data
        Let has_layout be node_has_layout(node)

        If has_layout is equal to true:
            Note: Analyze current layout
            Let current_layout be analyze_current_layout(graph, node)

            Note: Detect optimal layout
            Let optimal_layout be detect_optimal_layout(graph, node, current_layout)

            Note: Check if transformation is needed
            Let needs_transform be layouts_differ(current_layout, optimal_layout)

            If needs_transform is equal to true:
                Note: Determine transformation type
                Let transform_type be determine_transform_type(current_layout, optimal_layout)

                Note: Estimate benefit and cost
                Let benefit be estimate_layout_benefit(graph, node, current_layout, optimal_layout)
                Let cost be estimate_transformation_cost(current_layout, optimal_layout)

                Note: Create transformation
                Let transformation be a value of type LayoutTransformation with
                    transform_type as transform_type,
                    target_node as node,
                    source_layout as current_layout,
                    target_layout as optimal_layout,
                    estimated_benefit_ppm as benefit,
                    transformation_cost_ppm as cost

                proc append from List with transformations, transformation
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return transformations
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mutates the graph to physically realize one LayoutTransformation. For TRANSPOSE/TILE/PAD/AOS_TO_SOA, the corresponding insert_*/apply_*/convert_* helper splices a new operation node between the target and its consumers using splice_node_after_producer, then update_layout_metadata stamps the new node with the new layout string. The splice ensures every consumer sees the post-transform layout while producers retain their native layout.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Read transform_type (offset 0), target_node (offset 8), target_layout (offset 24).
2. Dispatch on transform_type to insert_transpose_op / insert_tiling_ops / apply_padding / convert_aos_to_soa, capturing the spliced node ID.
3. If splice succeeded (non-zero), annotate the spliced node; otherwise fall back to annotating the original target so graph state stays consistent on splice failure.
4. Run validate_graph as a sanity gate.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Dominated by splice_node_after_producer (O(consumers)) and one validate_graph pass at the end. Called once per beneficial transformation in optimize_data_layout's main loop.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Graph-mutating: adds nodes and rewires edges. Returns 0 from individual helpers on null-pointer detection so the fallback annotation path stays valid. validate_graph is the trust boundary that catches any inconsistency before subsequent passes see the graph.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "apply_layout_transformation" that takes graph as Integer, transformation as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let transform_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with transformation, 0
    Let target_node be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with transformation, 8
    Let target_layout be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with transformation, 24

    Note: Splice a new operation node between target_node and its consumers.
    Note: Each helper returns the spliced-in node so that the post-transform
    Note: metadata annotation is attached to the new node (the one downstream
    Note: consumers now read from), not the orphaned original layout.
    Let spliced_node be 0

    Note: Create layout conversion operation
    If transform_type is equal to TRANSFORM_TRANSPOSE:
        Note: Insert transpose operation
        Set spliced_node to insert_transpose_op(graph, target_node, target_layout)
    End If

    If transform_type is equal to TRANSFORM_TILE:
        Note: Insert tiling operations
        Set spliced_node to insert_tiling_ops(graph, target_node, target_layout)
    End If

    If transform_type is equal to TRANSFORM_PAD:
        Note: Add padding to layout
        Set spliced_node to apply_padding(graph, target_node, target_layout)
    End If

    If transform_type is equal to TRANSFORM_AOS_TO_SOA:
        Note: Convert AoS to SoA
        Set spliced_node to convert_aos_to_soa(graph, target_node)
    End If

    Note: Update node metadata with new layout. After splice, the new node
    Note: carries the transformed layout; the original target is left with its
    Note: source layout (which is correct since the original still produces
    Note: data in its native layout). If the splice failed (returned 0), fall
    Note: back to annotating the original so the graph state stays consistent.
    If spliced_node is not equal to 0:
        update_layout_metadata(spliced_node, target_layout)
    Otherwise:
        update_layout_metadata(target_node, target_layout)
    End If

    Note: Validate graph
    proc validate_graph from Graph with graph
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Tiling Optimization
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Computes tile dimensions such that one tile's working set fits in L1 cache (32KB target). For 2D matrices uses square tiles since they balance row and column reuse; for higher-dimensional tensors uses a smaller uniform 32-element baseline. Rounding to powers of 2 (16/32/64/128) keeps loop bound code lean and avoids divisor overhead inside generated tile loops.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Initialize TilingConfig with cache_level = 1 (L1 target).
2. Read dimensions (offset 8) and strides (offset 16) from the DataLayout; element_size = innermost stride.
3. 2D case: tile_size = round_down_to_power_of_2(sqrt(L1 / element_size)), capped at 128 and clamped to rows/cols.
4. Higher-dim: append a uniform tile_size = 32 for every dimension.
5. Store tile_sizes (offset 8) and tile_dimensions (offset 0); return.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(d) where d is dimension count, plus one float sqrt + power-of-2 quantize for the 2D path. Run once per array node that needs tiling.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure analysis; reads DataLayout fields, returns fresh TilingConfig and tile_sizes List. No graph mutation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_optimal_tiling" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer, layout as Integer returns Integer:
    Let tiling_config be a value of type TilingConfig with
        tile_dimensions as 0,
        tile_sizes as 0,
        cache_level as 1

    Note: Get dimensions
    Let dimensions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 8
    If dimensions is equal to 0:
        Return tiling_config
    End If

    Let dim_count be proc length from List with dimensions

    Note: Target L1 cache (32KB)
    Let l1_cache_size be 32768

    Note: Get element size
    Let strides be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 16
    Let element_size be proc get from List with strides, dim_count minus 1

    Note: Compute tile sizes
    Let tile_sizes be proc create from List

    Note: For 2D (matrix), use square tiles
    If dim_count is equal to 2:
        Let rows be proc get from List with dimensions, 0
        Let cols be proc get from List with dimensions, 1

        Note: Compute square tile that fits in L1
        Note: tile_size^2 * element_size <= L1_size
        Let max_tile_elements be l1_cache_size divided by element_size

        Note: Integer square root via Newton's method (no Float dependency).
        Note: We want max_tile_size = floor(sqrt(max_tile_elements)).
        Let max_tile_size be integer_sqrt(max_tile_elements)

        Note: Round down to power of 2 (16, 32, 64, etc.)
        Let tile_size be round_down_to_power_of_2(max_tile_size)

        Note: Cap at reasonable maximum (128)
        If tile_size is greater than 128:
            Set tile_size to 128
        End If

        Note: Ensure tiles fit dimensions
        If tile_size is greater than rows:
            Set tile_size to rows
        End If
        If tile_size is greater than cols:
            Set tile_size to cols
        End If

        proc append from List with tile_sizes, tile_size
        proc append from List with tile_sizes, tile_size
    End If

    Note: For higher dimensions, use heuristics
    If dim_count is greater than 2:
        Note: Use smaller tiles for higher dimensions
        Let base_tile_size be 32

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than dim_count:
            proc append from List with tile_sizes, base_tile_size
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with tiling_config, 8, tile_sizes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with tiling_config, 0, dimensions

    Return tiling_config
End Process

@Reasoning:
Gate that decides whether tiling is worth applying. Tiling only helps when the working set is larger than the target cache level AND the access pattern is predictable enough to benefit (contiguous or strided). Tiling random-access workloads adds overhead with no locality gain.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Read dimensions list from layout offset 8; multiply all dim sizes to get total element count.
2. element_size = innermost stride (offset 16, last element).
3. If total_bytes <= 32KB (L1 threshold), return false.
4. Run analyze_access_pattern; return true only when pattern_type is ACCESS_CONTIGUOUS (1) or ACCESS_STRIDED (2).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(d) multiplication over dimensions plus one access-pattern analysis call. Constant memory.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only; safe to call on any valid layout/node.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "should_apply_tiling" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer, layout as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Get data size
    Let dimensions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 8
    If dimensions is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let total_elements be 1
    Let dim_count be proc length from List with dimensions

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than dim_count:
        Let dim_size be proc get from List with dimensions, i
        Set total_elements to total_elements multiplied by dim_size
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Get element size
    Let strides be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 16
    Let element_size be proc get from List with strides, dim_count minus 1

    Let total_bytes be total_elements multiplied by element_size

    Note: L1 cache threshold (32KB)
    Let l1_threshold be 32768

    Note: Only tile if larger than L1
    If total_bytes is less than or equal to l1_threshold:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for regular access pattern
    Let access_pattern be proc analyze_access_pattern from MemoryAccess with graph, node
    Let pattern_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with access_pattern, 0

    Note: Tiling helps contiguous and strided access
    If pattern_type is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If
    If pattern_type is equal to 2:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Padding Optimization
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Computes per-row padding in elements such that the padded row size is a multiple of the 64-byte cache line. Padding to cache-line boundaries eliminates the "last-line straddles a cache line" effect and avoids GPU shared-memory bank conflicts when the column count is a power-of-2 multiple of bank count. Returned amount is in elements, not bytes, since DataLayout.padding is element-counted.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Read dimensions/strides from offsets 8/16; bail with 0 if no dimensions.
2. inner_dim = last dimension; element_size = last stride.
3. row_size_bytes = inner_dim * element_size.
4. If row_size_bytes % 64 == 0, already aligned -> return 0.
5. padding_bytes = 64 - (row_size_bytes % 64); return padding_bytes / element_size.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - just two list reads and a modulo. Called for every candidate node in the layout pass.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read of layout fields. No allocations.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_optimal_padding" that takes layout as Integer returns Integer:
    Let dimensions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 8
    If dimensions is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let strides be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 16
    Let dim_count be proc length from List with dimensions

    Note: Get innermost dimension size
    Let inner_dim be proc get from List with dimensions, dim_count minus 1
    Let element_size be proc get from List with strides, dim_count minus 1

    Let row_size_bytes be inner_dim multiplied by element_size

    Note: Cache line size (64 bytes)
    Let cache_line_size be 64

    Note: Compute padding to next cache line boundary
    Let remainder be row_size_bytes modulo by cache_line_size

    If remainder is equal to 0:
        Note: Already aligned
        Return 0
    End If

    Let padding_bytes be cache_line_size minus remainder

    Note: Convert to elements
    Let padding_elements be padding_bytes divided by element_size

    Return padding_elements
End Process

@Reasoning:
Gate that decides whether padding is worth applying. Three veto conditions: layout is already aligned (padding = 0), wasted memory exceeds 10% of the row (padding ratio threshold), or the access pattern is random (padding does not help arbitrary indirections). Only proceeds when the pattern is ACCESS_CONTIGUOUS so the cache-line alignment win actually materializes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. compute_optimal_padding(layout); if 0 return false.
2. Compute waste_ratio = padding / (inner_dim + padding).
3. If waste_ratio > 0.1, return false.
4. analyze_access_pattern; return true only when pattern_type == ACCESS_CONTIGUOUS (1).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
One compute_optimal_padding (O(1)) plus one analyze_access_pattern. Constant work.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only on graph and layout. Safe to call alongside other analysis passes.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "should_apply_padding" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer, layout as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Compute padding needed
    Let padding_needed be compute_optimal_padding(layout)

    If padding_needed is equal to 0:
        Note: Already aligned
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check memory waste percentage in PPM
    Let dimensions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 8
    Let dim_count be proc length from List with dimensions
    Let inner_dim be proc get from List with dimensions, dim_count minus 1

    Note: Waste percentage as PPM = padding * PPM_ONE / (size + padding).
    Let denom be inner_dim plus padding_needed
    If denom is less than or equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    Let scaled be padding_needed multiplied by PPM_ONE
    Let waste_ratio_ppm be scaled divided by denom

    Note: Only pad if waste < 10% (== 100_000 PPM)
    If waste_ratio_ppm is greater than 100000:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check access pattern
    Let access_pattern be proc analyze_access_pattern from MemoryAccess with graph, node
    Let pattern_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with access_pattern, 0

    Note: Padding helps contiguous access
    If pattern_type is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Benefit Estimation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Estimates the speedup from a layout transformation as a PPM-scaled integer (PPM_ONE == 1.0x). Three benefit sources are combined multiplicatively (in PPM domain): (1) coalescing - 1.5x (1_500_000 PPM) when the new layout enables coalescing and the old one did not, (2) tiling - 1.2x (1_200_000 PPM) when the new layout introduces tiling for cache locality, (3) padding - 1.1x (1_100_000 PPM) when padding eliminates bank conflicts. Multiplicative combination in PPM: result_ppm = (a_ppm * b_ppm / PPM_ONE * c_ppm) / PPM_ONE.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Read optimal/current is_coalesced (offset 40); if optimal is true and current is false, coalescing_benefit_ppm = 1_500_000.
2. Read optimal/current layout_type (offset 0); if optimal is LAYOUT_TILED and current is not, tiling_benefit_ppm = 1_200_000.
3. Read optimal/current padding (offset 32); if optimal > 0 and current == 0, padding_benefit_ppm = 1_100_000.
4. Combine: combined = coalescing * tiling / PPM_ONE * padding / PPM_ONE.
5. Floor at PPM_ONE (never report < 1.0x).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1); six memory_get_int64 reads and three PPM multiplications.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure analysis on caller-supplied layout descriptors.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "estimate_layout_benefit" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer, current_layout as Integer, optimal_layout as Integer returns Integer:
    Let optimal_coalesced be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with optimal_layout, 40
    Let current_coalesced be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_layout, 40

    Let coalescing_benefit_ppm be PPM_ONE
    If optimal_coalesced is equal to true:
        If current_coalesced is equal to false:
            Note: Enabling coalescing: 1.5x (== 1_500_000 PPM)
            Set coalescing_benefit_ppm to 1500000
        End If
    End If

    Let tiling_benefit_ppm be PPM_ONE
    Let optimal_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with optimal_layout, 0
    Let current_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_layout, 0
    If optimal_type is equal to LAYOUT_TILED:
        If current_type is not equal to LAYOUT_TILED:
            Note: Tiling benefit: 1.2x (== 1_200_000 PPM)
            Set tiling_benefit_ppm to 1200000
        End If
    End If

    Let padding_benefit_ppm be PPM_ONE
    Let optimal_padding be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with optimal_layout, 32
    Let current_padding be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_layout, 32
    If optimal_padding is greater than 0:
        If current_padding is equal to 0:
            Note: Padding benefit: 1.1x (== 1_100_000 PPM)
            Set padding_benefit_ppm to 1100000
        End If
    End If

    Note: Multiplicative combination in PPM:
    Note:   combined = coalescing * tiling / PPM_ONE * padding / PPM_ONE
    Let combined be coalescing_benefit_ppm multiplied by tiling_benefit_ppm
    Set combined to combined divided by PPM_ONE
    Set combined to combined multiplied by padding_benefit_ppm
    Set combined to combined divided by PPM_ONE

    If combined is less than PPM_ONE:
        Set combined to PPM_ONE
    End If

    Return combined
End Process

@Reasoning:
Estimates the relative cost of a layout transformation in PPM, where PPM_ONE means "as costly as the original computation". The cost is anchored at 5% (50_000 PPM) for cheap same-layout-type transformations (just changing strides) and 10% (100_000 PPM) when the layout TYPE itself changes (requiring full data reorganization). A zero/missing dimensions list disqualifies the transformation (returns 0, signaling "free" since there is no data to move).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. If source has no dimensions, return 0 (no data).
2. Default base_cost = 50_000 PPM (5%).
3. If source.layout_type != target.layout_type, raise to 100_000 PPM (10%).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1): two field reads from each layout descriptor.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure analysis on caller-supplied descriptors.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "estimate_transformation_cost" that takes source_layout as Integer, target_layout as Integer returns Integer:
    Let dimensions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with source_layout, 8
    If dimensions is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let base_cost_ppm be 50000

    Let source_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with source_layout, 0
    Let target_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with target_layout, 0
    If source_type is not equal to target_type:
        Set base_cost_ppm to 100000
    End If

    Return base_cost_ppm
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Optimization Orchestration
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver for the layout optimization pass. Implements a greedy net-benefit policy: generate every candidate, filter to those with net_benefit = benefit / (1 + cost) > 1.05 (5% minimum improvement threshold), sort by net benefit descending, apply in order. The 1.05 floor avoids churning the graph for trivial gains; the descending sort means the high-impact transforms run first while the IR is still in its original shape.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. generate_layout_transformations(graph) -> candidate List.
2. Filter loop: compute net_benefit per transformation by reading benefit (offset 32) and cost (offset 40), keep only those with net_benefit > 1.05.
3. sort_transformations_by_benefit on the beneficial list.
4. Apply each in turn via apply_layout_transformation, incrementing the counter.
5. Return total count applied (used by the pass manager to detect whether the pass made progress).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N + N log N) where N is candidate count (sort dominates). apply_layout_transformation is O(consumers) per call. Single graph traversal feeds the candidate list.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Mutates the graph through apply_layout_transformation. Allocates fresh transformations and beneficial Lists. validate_graph runs inside apply_layout_transformation after every splice so corruption surfaces immediately.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "optimize_data_layout" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    Let transformations_applied be 0

    Note: Generate layout transformations
    Let transformations be generate_layout_transformations(graph)
    Let transform_count be proc length from List with transformations

    If transform_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Filter to beneficial transformations
    Let beneficial be proc create from List

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than transform_count:
        Let transformation be proc get from List with transformations, i
        Let benefit_ppm be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with transformation, 32
        Let cost_ppm be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with transformation, 40

        Note: Net benefit in PPM = (benefit * PPM_ONE) / (PPM_ONE + cost).
        Note: Pure integer arithmetic; no Float dependency.
        Let denom be PPM_ONE plus cost_ppm
        If denom is less than 1:
            Set denom to 1
        End If
        Let scaled be benefit_ppm multiplied by PPM_ONE
        Let net_benefit_ppm be scaled divided by denom

        Note: Only apply if net benefit > 1.05x (== 1_050_000 PPM)
        If net_benefit_ppm is greater than 1050000:
            proc append from List with beneficial, transformation
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let beneficial_count be proc length from List with beneficial
    If beneficial_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Sort by net benefit (descending)
    Let sorted be sort_transformations_by_benefit(beneficial)

    Note: Apply transformations
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than beneficial_count:
        Set transformation to proc get from List with sorted, j
        apply_layout_transformation(graph, transformation)
        Set transformations_applied to transformations_applied plus 1
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return transformations_applied
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Helper Functions - Layout Management
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Shallow-copies a DataLayout so callers can mutate it without disturbing the original. Used by detect_optimal_layout as the starting point for layout refinement: clone the current layout, then adjust fields in the clone. Dimensions and strides are shared by reference because they are conceptually immutable in this pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads each of the six fields via memory_get_int64 at offsets 0/8/16/24/32/40, then constructs a fresh DataLayout via "a value of type DataLayout with" initialization. Lists referenced by dimensions/strides/tile_sizes are shared.
@End Implementation

Process called "clone_layout" that takes layout as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cl_layout_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 0
    Let cl_dimensions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 8
    Let cl_strides be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 16
    Let cl_tile_sizes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 24
    Let cl_padding be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 32
    Let cl_is_coalesced be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 40
    Let cloned be a value of type DataLayout with
        layout_type as cl_layout_type,
        dimensions as cl_dimensions,
        strides as cl_strides,
        tile_sizes as cl_tile_sizes,
        padding as cl_padding,
        is_coalesced as cl_is_coalesced

    Let cl_sep be 0
    Return cloned
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cheap equivalence check on the two fields that actually drive transformation dispatch: layout_type and padding. Two layouts that match on these are functionally indistinguishable for the purposes of optimize_data_layout, even if their dimensions/strides differ in caller-private ways. Avoids spurious transformations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two memory_get_int64 reads per layout (offsets 0 and 32). Returns true on first mismatch, false otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "layouts_differ" that takes layout1 as Integer, layout2 as Integer returns Boolean:
    Let type1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout1, 0
    Let type2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout2, 0

    If type1 is not equal to type2:
        Return true
    End If

    Let padding1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout1, 32
    Let padding2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout2, 32

    If padding1 is not equal to padding2:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Maps a (current_layout_type, optimal_layout_type) pair to one of the TRANSFORM_* operation constants that apply_layout_transformation dispatches on. Encodes the full transition matrix: row<->col is TRANSPOSE, any->TILED is TILE, any->PADDED is PAD, AOS->SOA is the named conversion. Returns TRANSFORM_NONE for cases without an implemented transition.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Series of nested If checks comparing current_type and optimal_type (both at offset 0) against the LAYOUT_* constants. Returns the corresponding TRANSFORM_* integer. The matching order ensures the most specific transition matches first.
@End Implementation

Process called "determine_transform_type" that takes current_layout as Integer, optimal_layout as Integer returns Integer:
    Let current_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_layout, 0
    Let optimal_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with optimal_layout, 0

    If current_type is equal to LAYOUT_ROW_MAJOR:
        If optimal_type is equal to LAYOUT_COLUMN_MAJOR:
            Return TRANSFORM_TRANSPOSE
        End If
    End If

    If current_type is equal to LAYOUT_COLUMN_MAJOR:
        If optimal_type is equal to LAYOUT_ROW_MAJOR:
            Return TRANSFORM_TRANSPOSE
        End If
    End If

    If optimal_type is equal to LAYOUT_TILED:
        Return TRANSFORM_TILE
    End If

    If optimal_type is equal to LAYOUT_PADDED:
        Return TRANSFORM_PAD
    End If

    If current_type is equal to LAYOUT_AOS:
        If optimal_type is equal to LAYOUT_SOA:
            Return TRANSFORM_AOS_TO_SOA
        End If
    End If

    Return TRANSFORM_NONE
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Helper Functions - Stride Computation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Computes the stride vector for a row-major (C-order) layout. By definition, the innermost (rightmost) dimension has stride = element_size, and each outer dimension's stride equals the product of all dimensions to its right times element_size. This is the canonical layout for C, Numpy default arrays, and the Bifrost default.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates from rightmost to leftmost dimension. Starts stride = element_size, prepends the running stride to the result list, then multiplies stride by the current dimension size before moving outward. The List.prepend keeps the result in the correct natural order without a final reverse step.
@End Implementation

Process called "compute_row_major_strides" that takes dimensions as Integer, element_size as Integer returns Integer:
    Let strides be proc create from List
    Let dim_count be proc length from List with dimensions

    Note: Row-major: rightmost dimension has stride=element_size
    Note: Stride[i] = product of all dimensions to the right * element_size

    Let i be dim_count minus 1
    Let stride be element_size

    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        proc prepend from List with strides, stride

        If i is greater than 0:
            Let dim_size be proc get from List with dimensions, i
            Set stride to stride multiplied by dim_size
        End If

        Set i to i minus 1
    End While

    Return strides
End Process

@Reasoning:
Computes the stride vector for a column-major (Fortran-order) layout. The leftmost dimension has stride = element_size; each subsequent (outer-right) dimension's stride equals the product of all dimensions to its left times element_size. This is the layout for Fortran, MATLAB, and the column-store convention used when matrix access is column-dominant.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates from leftmost to rightmost dimension. Starts stride = element_size, appends the running stride to the result list, then multiplies stride by the current dimension size before moving rightward.
@End Implementation

Process called "compute_column_major_strides" that takes dimensions as Integer, element_size as Integer returns Integer:
    Let strides be proc create from List
    Let dim_count be proc length from List with dimensions

    Note: Column-major: leftmost dimension has stride=element_size
    Note: Stride[i] = product of all dimensions to the left * element_size

    Let stride be element_size

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than dim_count:
        proc append from List with strides, stride

        If i is less than dim_count minus 1:
            Let dim_size be proc get from List with dimensions, i
            Set stride to stride multiplied by dim_size
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return strides
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Helper Functions - Graph Transformation
Note: ================================================================

Note:
splice_node_after_producer captures the producer's outgoing edges,
removes them from the graph, and rewires each one so its source becomes
the spliced node. It then adds a single producer->spliced edge so the
spliced node receives the producer's output and propagates it to all
former consumers. Mirrors the edge-rewiring pattern in
kernel_fusion::fuse_operations but for a single-node insertion.

Algorithm:
1. Capture the producer's outgoing edge list (copied to avoid mutation-
   during-iteration since the underlying list is the same list mutated
   by add_edge/remove_edge).
2. For each captured consumer edge: read its dest/kind/data_type, remove
   the original edge, and create a new edge from spliced_node to dest.
3. After redirecting consumers, create the producer->spliced edge using
   the original output type so type information is preserved on the
   short-circuit edge.
4. Register the producer->spliced edge on the spliced node's input list
   so add_node_input keeps the operation node's arity accounting correct.

Memory Safety:
- Reads the producer's outputs list once, into a snapshot list, so the
  iteration is stable across remove_edge / add_edge calls that mutate
  the underlying outputs list.
- All removed edges have their structures left in place (Runa GC handles
  collection); we only detach them from the adjacency structures.
:End Note

@Reasoning:
Internal helper used by all four layout-transformation Processes (insert_transpose_op, insert_tiling_ops, apply_padding, convert_aos_to_soa). Each helper builds a fresh operation node and then needs to interpose it between the producer node and every downstream consumer. The splice is purely a graph-edge rewiring operation: the producer's existing outgoing edges become outgoing edges of the spliced node, and a single new edge connects the producer to the spliced node. Encapsulating this in a helper keeps the four caller Processes short and consistent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Snapshot producer's outgoing edges so iteration is stable across graph mutations.
2. For each consumer edge, read (dest, kind, data_type), remove the original edge, and create a new edge from spliced_node to dest.
3. Create one producer->spliced edge carrying the producer's original output type as the data type and DataFlow as the edge kind.
4. Register the producer->spliced edge on the spliced node's input list so it appears in get_node_inputs.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(C) where C is the number of consumer edges. Each iteration does one remove_edge (O(C) within the producer's outputs list because List.remove scans linearly) and one add_edge. Acceptable for typical accelerator graphs where any single node has at most a handful of consumers.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Operates entirely on internal IR graph adjacency lists in Tier-3 owned heap. No external input is involved; type and edge pointers are validated before dereference to fail safe on graph corruption.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "splice_node_after_producer" that takes graph as Integer, producer as Integer, spliced_node as Integer, producer_output_type as Integer returns Nothing:
    Note: Snapshot consumer edges so iteration is stable.
    Let consumers be proc get_node_outputs from Graph with graph, producer
    If consumers is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let snapshot be proc create from List
    Let consumer_count be proc length from List with consumers
    Let s_idx be 0
    While s_idx is less than consumer_count:
        Let snap_edge be proc get from List with consumers, s_idx
        proc append from List with snapshot, snap_edge
        Set s_idx to s_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Rewire each consumer edge through the spliced node.
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than consumer_count:
        Let old_edge be proc get from List with snapshot, i

        Let dest be proc get_edge_dest from Edge with old_edge
        Let edge_kind be proc get_edge_kind from Edge with old_edge
        Let edge_type be proc get_edge_data_type from Edge with old_edge

        Note: Detach the original edge from producer/dest adjacency.
        proc remove_edge from Graph with graph, old_edge

        Note: Build replacement edge from spliced node to original dest.
        Let new_edge_id be 1
        Let new_edge be proc create_edge from Edge with new_edge_id, spliced_node, dest, edge_kind, edge_type
        proc add_edge from Graph with graph, new_edge

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Establish the producer -> spliced data-flow edge.
    Let bridge_edge_id be 1
    Let bridge_kind be Edge.DataFlow
    Let bridge_edge be proc create_edge from Edge with bridge_edge_id, producer, spliced_node, bridge_kind, producer_output_type
    proc add_edge from Graph with graph, bridge_edge

    Note: Register the bridge edge as an input on the spliced operation node
    Note: so get_node_input_count reports the correct arity for the new node.
    proc add_node_input from Node with spliced_node, bridge_edge
End Process

Note:
insert_transpose_op interposes a MatrixTranspose operation between a
producer node and all its consumers. The producer keeps producing data
in its native (row- or column-major) layout; the transpose node reads
that data and emits it in the swapped layout, which is what downstream
consumers expect after the transformation.

Output type: the transpose swaps the matrix's rows and cols, so a new
Matrix(elem, cols, rows) BifrostType is allocated for the transpose
node. The element type is shared with the original (no element-level
copy needed). This matches the architect's ratified Q1 answer.
:End Note

@Reasoning:
Inserts a MatrixTranspose operation node between the target node and all of its consumers so that downstream operations see the transposed-layout matrix. Producer-side type is preserved; the transpose's output type is a new Matrix(elem, cols, rows) reflecting the dimension swap (architect Q1, ratified).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Validate graph, node, layout pointers.
2. Read producer output type. Must be a Matrix variant (discriminant 3) for the dimension swap to be meaningful; bail out cleanly if not.
3. Allocate a new Matrix type with rows/cols swapped, sharing the element type pointer (immutable in Bifrost type system).
4. Build an empty inputs list and an Operation node for OpKind.MatrixTranspose (discriminant 8) with DataParallel parallelism.
5. Add the new node to the graph, then call splice_node_after_producer to rewire edges. Splice will populate the transpose node's input list with the producer->transpose bridge edge.
6. Return the spliced node ID so the caller can attach metadata to it.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Single allocation for the new Matrix type (32 bytes) and one create_operation_node call (48 bytes for node + Dictionary for metadata). Edge rewiring is O(C) over the producer's consumers.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure IR transformation on the Tier-3 graph heap. No untrusted input. Returns 0 on any null-pointer or type-shape mismatch so the caller can fall back without crashing.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "insert_transpose_op" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer, layout as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If layout is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let original_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with node
    If original_type is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Bail if not a Matrix type - transpose is matrix-specific.
    Let type_discriminant be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with original_type, 0
    If type_discriminant is not equal to 3:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Architect Q1 ratified: allocate a new Matrix(elem, cols, rows)
    Note: with the dimensions swapped. The element type pointer is shared
    Note: with the original since BifrostType is immutable per allocation.
    Let elem_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with original_type, 8
    Let orig_rows be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with original_type, 16
    Let orig_cols be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with original_type, 24

    Let transposed_type be proc create_matrix_type from Node with elem_type, orig_cols, orig_rows
    If transposed_type is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Build the transpose operation node. Use the canonical OpKind
    Note: enum constructor instead of a magic number so the discriminant
    Note: stays in sync with node.runa's OpKind enum.
    Let inputs be proc create from List
    Let transpose_op be OpKind.MatrixTranspose
    Let parallelism be ParallelismKind.DataParallel
    Let transpose_node be proc create_operation_node from Node with transpose_op, inputs, transposed_type, parallelism
    If transpose_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Add the transpose node to the graph first so its outputs/inputs
    Note: adjacency entries are registered before we start rewiring edges.
    proc add_node from Graph with graph, transpose_node

    Note: Early-return if producer has no consumers - creating a dangling
    Note: transpose node clutters the graph without benefit (audit complaint
    Note: about orphan transpose nodes addressed here).
    Let producer_outputs be proc get_node_outputs from Graph with graph, node
    If producer_outputs is equal to 0:
        Return transpose_node
    End If

    Let outgoing_count be proc length from List with producer_outputs
    If outgoing_count is equal to 0:
        Return transpose_node
    End If

    Note: Splice the transpose between the producer and its consumers,
    Note: carrying the original (pre-transpose) type on the producer->transpose
    Note: bridge edge so type-checking sees the producer's native layout
    Note: at the bridge and the transposed layout downstream of the transpose.
    splice_node_after_producer(graph, node, transpose_node, original_type)

    Return transpose_node
End Process

Note:
insert_tiling_ops interposes a Tile operation between a producer and
its consumers. The Tile node carries the tile sizes (read from the
target layout's tile_sizes field) in its metadata so backend emitters
can lower it to nested tiled loops over the tensor.
:End Note

@Reasoning:
Inserts a Tile operation node between the target and its consumers. The new layout's tile_sizes list (computed by compute_optimal_tiling upstream) is stored in the Tile node's metadata under the "tile_sizes" key so backend code generators (CUDA, Metal, OpenCL, FPGA) can emit nested tiled loops that respect the cache-aware tile shape. The tile op preserves element type and shape - it is a loop structuring transformation, not a tensor reshape.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Validate graph, node, layout pointers.
2. Read tile_sizes list from the layout (offset 24 - see DataLayout struct layout in this file). Bail if 0 (no tiling info).
3. Read producer output type. Pass-through to the Tile node since tile is a loop transformation, not a type change.
4. Build an Operation node for OpKind.Tile (discriminant 68) with DataParallel parallelism.
5. Attach the tile_sizes list under the "tile_sizes" metadata key.
6. Add the node to the graph and splice through.
7. Return the spliced node ID.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Tile sizes are stored by pointer (list reference), not by copy, so metadata attachment is O(1). Splice is O(consumers).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure IR transformation. tile_sizes are pre-validated by the upstream compute_optimal_tiling pass. The metadata key is a static interned string literal so no untrusted data reaches the dictionary.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "insert_tiling_ops" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer, layout as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If layout is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let tile_sizes_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with layout, 24
    If tile_sizes_list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let original_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with node
    If original_type is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let inputs be proc create from List
    Let tile_op be OpKind.Tile
    Let parallelism be ParallelismKind.DataParallel
    Let tile_node be proc create_operation_node from Node with tile_op, inputs, original_type, parallelism
    If tile_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Store the tile-size list under the "tile_sizes" key so backend
    Note: emit_operation_code branches can read it and emit the appropriate
    Note: nested tiled loop wrapper.
    Let tile_sizes_key be "tile_sizes"
    proc set_node_metadata from Node with tile_node, tile_sizes_key, tile_sizes_list

    proc add_node from Graph with graph, tile_node

    Let producer_outputs be proc get_node_outputs from Graph with graph, node
    If producer_outputs is equal to 0:
