    Return tile_node
End Process

Note:
apply_padding interposes a Pad operation between a producer and its
consumers. The Pad node carries the padding amount (element count, not
bytes) under the "pad_amount" key and a zero fill value under the
"pad_value" key. Backend emitters allocate the padded buffer and emit
a guarded copy whose innermost dimension is aligned per the metadata.
:End Note

@Reasoning:
Inserts a Pad operation node carrying the padding amount in metadata. Architect Q2: pad fill value is hard-coded "0" - layout padding is dead space, so the fill never represents a meaningful value. If a future call site needs non-zero padding it can override the "pad_value" metadata key after the splice.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Validate graph, node, layout pointers.
2. Read padding element count from layout offset 32 (DataLayout.padding). Bail if 0 (no padding needed - the layout is already aligned).
3. Read producer output type. Pass-through (padding does not change element type, only changes the buffer shape along the innermost dimension; that's encoded in metadata so backend allocators know).
4. Build an Operation node for OpKind.Pad (discriminant 67) with DataParallel parallelism.
5. Attach "pad_amount" = padding_elements and "pad_value" = "0".
6. Add to graph and splice through.
7. Return the spliced node ID.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Metadata attachment is O(1) per key. Splice is O(consumers).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pad amount is pre-validated by compute_optimal_padding. The "0" fill value is a string literal under control of the compiler; no untrusted input ever reaches metadata.
@End Security_Scope

